@mattacus Good question, let me try to clarify more. Let's try to go through an example and I'll walk through how the new mid trade risk profiling will work. Let's say you open a 1x LONG position on bitcoin, with the expectation that Bitcoin will rise in price. This happens at 11:00, when the price of bitcoin is 65000 USD. At 11:01, the price of bitcoin goes to 65650 - this represents a 1% gain. At 11:02, the price of bitcoin drops to 65350. This represents a 0.4% loss relative to the last point, 65650. Finally, there is one more loss from 11:02 to 11:03, to 65100 - a 0.38% loss, before you close the position. Your omega would be calculated as log(1.01) / abs(log(0.996) + log(0.9962)) = 1.27. Omega will always be greater than 1 if the original return was positive.

A couple of things to note - the gains and losses (percent increase and decrease) are always calculated against the prior value, and we will be measuring them at an incredibly high frequency. So there's not a clear answer to your question- a miner with a LONG hold strategy for bitcoin may still do well in our system, but only when bitcoin is currently increasing in value, prior gains on bitcoin will only marginally benefit the miner (the same historical decay will apply). A miner with smaller, consistent returns will only do well if they are able their smaller trades correctly time market movement. There is however constant historical decay, so miners with open positions that are correctly capturing market movement will have the least amount of historical decay, as they are providing the most recent information to the network.

We also have a 10% total drawdown rate at any given time, the combo of 5% daily dd and 10% max all time dd seems to be fairly common among other prop firms. This may change if mid trade risk profiling is incredibly successful at managing risk, we'll see.

@ptn・8  I am excited to announce the release of our new mid-trade risk profiling system. This system will give us a new level of precision in measuring the quality of our miner’s strategies and risk utilization.

**Details on Gains / Losses**
To achieve this, we are now measuring the value changes of each miner throughout the duration of holding onto a position. Any time the position increases in value, the miner will accumulate a gain by augmenting the increase by the leverage. The same process will happen for losses. With this new system, open and closed positions will be evaluated the same way, based on their delta changes to the portfolio. Thus, any open position may actively count against you if it is dropping in value. Historical decay will work the same as it was before, but now using miner checkpoints, which contain information about the miner gains and losses over each period. Thus the miners who are more active in correctly tracking market movement are likely to be more competitive. Additionally, we are requiring a minimum of 15 minutes for each 6 hour interval to qualify for scoring in that round.

@kabar  with the new system, current open positions are incentivized to be tracking only positive gains. The aggregation of all open positions can always be thought of as a real time signal for trading - at any given moment you should be able to open new positions held by the miners and capture benefits. This is a bit different from before, where you might need to enter at the same time as the miner to capture their benefit.

@Terps , challenge with commit reveal is enabling the validators to score the position without knowing which asset is being traded.

We’re going to look into tweaking the incentive for more returns and less risk mitigation, incorporation of a baseline, and reduction of time constraints on checkpoints. Thanks for the feedback everyone, you guys are great 🙏

@Whit_Delta Right now we use a 6 hour checkpoint period, which means historical decay won't have an impact yet in this scenario (we have some plans to fix this in the next couple of weeks). Right now, you'll be tracked with a 2% gain and a 2% loss, so your return would be ~0%, your Omega would be 1, and your sortino would be 2% / 1hr20min (tracks the losses, lower is better). Returns are now the dominant source of the score, so it is unlikely your miner would be in the top position and you would likely get penalized for your relatively high sortino.

@ZHawk shooting to be slightly less fast and furious, fine balance at play here among metrics- hoping the changes get more and more incremental
@mattacus scoring is now rolled out to the new distribution, higher historical relevance on omega/sortino coming shortly

@ZHawk No worries, I know it's a lot of moving parts, apologies for the challenge with keeping up. The change to priority in scoring was quite straightforward, and recent returns will continue to dominate the scoring function, so returns based miners with decent risk management are unlikely to be significantly impacted with new decay - the relative significance of each feature will stay the same but the history used to compose them will change slightly. The upcoming change to historical decay rate requires a bit more infrastructural change, so I'll need to test things more thoroughly before rollout.

@Whit_Delta I see. There might be a misunderstanding- we are tracking all movement on the position, and it will be attributed to the final score. Thus your gains parameter for the checkpoint will be 2%, your losses will be 0.5%, and your open_ms parameter will be 1hr20min. The details on scoring with these values can be found in the "cps" functions here (note gains and losses are in log format): https://github.com/taoshidev/proprietary-trading-network/blob/92b9f0aae36b149be43b52479fc20e543943140b/vali_objects/scoring/scoring.py#L109. Your returns for the checkpoint would be 1.5%, omega would be 2 / 0.5 = 4, sortino would be 0.5 / 1hr20min
We don't have a 6 hour rule, 6 hours is just a byproduct of the compression scheme we created to store deltas information in a more compressed way for the validators, this is likely to change.

